Scores of indigene of Ayedire, Olaoluwa and part of Iwo local government areas of Osun State on Monday thronged the street of Osogbo, Osun state capital to protest the alleged assault on one the Royal fathers in their domains. The protesters that included Chiefs and prominent sons and daughters of Ogbaagba, Ile-Ogbo and other communities staged the peaceful protest to register their dissatisfaction at the way and manner the Oluwo of Iwo, Oba Abdulrosheed Adewale Akanbi allegedly beat up the Agbowu of Ogbaagbaa, Oba Dhirulahi Akinropo. It would be recalled that the Oluwo, who was invited to the Zone 11 police headquarters in Osogbo by the Assistant Inspector General of Police in charge of the zone, Bashir Makama’ on Friday attacked a fellow monarch at a supposed peace meeting conveyed by the AIG. The placard carrying members of the towns had mobilised themselves and stormed the Osun State Government Secretariat, Abeere to demonstrate against the alleged assault. They accused Governor of keeping mum since the incident happened last week Friday and urged him to react by reprimanding Oluwo with suspension. The protesters’ spokesperson, a former member of the State House of Assembly, Hon Sikiru Ogunlade Araoye explained that Governor Gboyega’s Oyetola’s indifference on the issue could cause communal clash between Iwo and other adjourning town, Ogbaagba, whose traditional ruler was assaulted. Meanwhile a statement issued on behalf of government by the state’s Commissioner for Information and Civic Orientation, Mrs. Funke Egbemode described as unfortunate and avoidable, the face-off between the two monarchs. The government said it is aware that the State Traditional Council is looking into the matter. It further stated that traditional rulers ought to protect and preserve the sacredness of traditional institutions. “Government noted that situations where royal fathers engage in public display of temperament do not edify the revered stools of our forebears.’’ 